doing: The company I work at has its own projects, but mostly we try to assist other bigger companies in solving problems that are too complex for them. When a company had issues with the performance of ROS2 it was quite difficult to understand the inner-workings of ROS2. I am aware that for the average user a full overview of how rclcpp, rcl and rmw work is not very useful, but it is quite a big hurdle for new people if they want to contribute to the ROS2 internals. The general overview is fine and it is easy to understand the layers at a conceptual level, but understanding how for instance the memory strategy and executor were implemented throughout the layers was quite tricky to figure out. I have mixed feelings writing this, because I'm quite certain we are more of an edge-case and the general public is probably less likely to fill in this form, so don't skew priority this way too much. Just wanted to mention/point out that there is an audience for this kind of in-depth information.

doing: I'm going to take this box as an opportunity for a general comment as opposed to answering the question. In coming into ROS as a software developer with some limited robotics experience, I found the documentation very frustrating. It seemed to discourage anyone with any software background from getting involved in that it talked mostly about high level concepts and never explained how any of the tools worked. It was also frustrating that the docs were really spread out. There's a wiki, there's some python docs, there's ROS answers (the answers in ROS answers should really be ported back to the documentation). Other projects do a much better job of documentation, like Eigen or CMake. Granted CMake is still not very easy to use, but at least they have detailed documentation under one roof. I would encourage a focus on consolidation and improving quality of low level documentation as opposed to covering more use cases.

doing:
Following up from my work at an ROV company called OpenROV (now Sofar Ocean Technology), I am working with a small team called Mission Robotics to build an open-source OS distro + development environment + CI/CD framework + embedded systems application library + base software collection for marine technology (ROVs, AUVs, surface vehicles, distributed sensor networks, etc) built on top of ROS2. I've heard that there may some somewhat related work happening at OSRF, and was wondering if it might be worth chatting at some point to see if there is any overlap or places where efforts can be combined.

Additionally, I am working on a telerobotics framework that allows remote, real-time connectivity over standard internet infrastructure between ROS2 systems and other software (think along the lines of a WebRTC bridge for ROS2).

Lastly, I currently work full time at an autonomous vehicle company that is using ROS1 + ApexOS + pure DDS.
